TY  - JOUR
T1  - Time and Organizational Improvisation
AU  - Crossan, Mary
AU  - Cunha, Miguel Pina E
AU  - Vera, Dusya
AU  - Cunha, João
Y1  - 2005/01/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.15281441
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.15281441
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 129
EP  - 145
VL  - 30
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We argue that effective management action is impeded by a simplistic understanding of time?one dominated by a clock-time perspective. Using the concept of improvisation, we reconcile two major time dichotomies associated with organizational phenomena: clock time versus event time and linear time versus cyclical time. We propose that improvisation offers a means for management theorists and practictioners to overcome these apparent time dichotomies.
AB  - We argue that effective management action is impeded by a simplistic understanding of time?one dominated by a clock-time perspective. Using the concept of improvisation, we reconcile two major time dichotomies associated with organizational phenomena: clock time versus event time and linear time versus cyclical time. We propose that improvisation offers a means for management theorists and practictioners to overcome these apparent time dichotomies.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.15281441
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2005.15281441
