TY  - JOUR
T1  - Economics Language and Assumptions: How Theories can Become Self-Fulfilling
AU  - Ferraro, Fabrizio
AU  - Pfeffer, Jeffrey
AU  - Sutton, Robert I.
Y1  - 2005/01/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.15281412
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.15281412
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 8
EP  - 24
VL  - 30
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Social science theories can become self-fulfilling by shaping institutional designs and management practices, as well as social norms and expectations about behavior, thereby creating the behavior they predict. They also perpetuate themselves by promulgating language and assumptions that become widely used and accepted. We illustrate these ideas by considering how the language and assumptions of economics shape management practices: theories can ?win? in the marketplace for ideas, independent of their empirical validity, to the extent their assumptions and language become taken for granted and normatively valued, therefore creating conditions that make them come ?true.?
AB  - Social science theories can become self-fulfilling by shaping institutional designs and management practices, as well as social norms and expectations about behavior, thereby creating the behavior they predict. They also perpetuate themselves by promulgating language and assumptions that become widely used and accepted. We illustrate these ideas by considering how the language and assumptions of economics shape management practices: theories can ?win? in the marketplace for ideas, independent of their empirical validity, to the extent their assumptions and language become taken for granted and normatively valued, therefore creating conditions that make them come ?true.?
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.15281412
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2005.15281412
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Role of Followers in the Charismatic Leadership Process: Relationships and Their Consequences
AU  - Howell, Jane M.
AU  - Shamir, Boas
Y1  - 2005/01/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.15281435
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.15281435
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 96
EP  - 112
VL  - 30
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We present a theoretical analysis of the follower's role in the charismatic leadership process. Specifically, we distinguish between two types of charismatic relationships?personalized and socialized?and present general propositions about how followers' self-concepts may determine the type of charismatic relationship they form with the leader. We then develop more specific propositions about the follower's role in various stages of the charismatic relationship process, and we conclude by outlining the implications of the propositions and suggesting further opportunities for theoretical extension.
AB  - We present a theoretical analysis of the follower's role in the charismatic leadership process. Specifically, we distinguish between two types of charismatic relationships?personalized and socialized?and present general propositions about how followers' self-concepts may determine the type of charismatic relationship they form with the leader. We then develop more specific propositions about the follower's role in various stages of the charismatic relationship process, and we conclude by outlining the implications of the propositions and suggesting further opportunities for theoretical extension.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.15281435
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2005.15281435
Y2  - 2026/04/24
